    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When it comes to indemnification clauses, there are some sneaky wording tricks that can catch you off guard. One common pitfall is the use of vague language, such as \"any and all\" or \"including without limitation.\" These phrases can be used to expand the scope of the clause beyond what you initially think.\n\nFor example, a clause might say: \"The Recipient shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Disclosing Party from and against any and all losses, damages, liabilities, deficiencies, claims, actions, judgments, settlements, interest, awards, penalties, fines, costs, or expenses of whatever kind, arising out of or occurring in connection with any breach or non-fulfillment of any representation, warranty, or covenant made by the Recipient.\"\n\nThe word \"arising out of\" can be particularly problematic, as it can be interpreted to include indirect consequences or \"ripple effects\" that you might not have anticipated. It's like a slippery slope, where one small mistake can lead to a cascade of downstream liabilities.\n\nAnother red flag is the use of \"reasonable attorneys' fees,\" which can be a costly and time-consuming way to defend yourself. It's like being forced to hire a team of lawyers to chase",
